04849nam a22006615i 9780231554077DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021039877  a97802315540777 a10.7312/zimr201382doi  a(DE-B1597)627229  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBF441 4aBF441b.Z55 2022 7aMAT0290002bisacsh04a153.4/2223/eng/202111041 aZimring, James C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPartial Truths :bHow Fractions Distort Our Thinking /cJames C. Zimring. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b11 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART 1: THE PROBLEM OF MISPERCEPTION -- t1. The Fraction Problem -- t2. How Our Minds Fractionate the World -- t3. Confirmation Bias: How Our Minds Evaluate Evidence Based on Preexisting Beliefs -- t4. Bias with a Cherry on Top: Cherry-Picking the Data -- tPART 2: THE FRACTION PROBLEM IN DIFFERENT ARENAS -- t5. The Criminal Justice System -- t6. The March to War -- t7. Patterns in the Static -- t8. Alternative and New Age Beliefs -- t9. The Appearance of Design in the Natural World -- t10. The Hard Sciences -- tPART 3: CAN WE REVERSE MISPERCEPTION AND SHOULD WE EVEN TRY? -- t11. How Misperceiving the Fraction Can Be Advantageous -- t12. Can We Solve the Problems with Human Perception and Reasoning and Should We Even Try? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA fast-food chain once tried to compete with McDonald’s quarter-pounder by introducing a third-pound hamburger—only for it to flop when consumers thought a third pound was less than a quarter pound because three is less than four. Separately, a rash of suicides by teenagers who played Dungeons and Dragons caused a panic in parents and the media. They thought D&D was causing teenage suicides—when in fact teenage D&D players died by suicide at a much lower rate than the national average. Errors of this type can be found from antiquity to the present, from the Peloponnesian War to the COVID-19 pandemic. How and why do we keep falling into these traps?James C. Zimring argues that many of the mistakes that the human mind consistently makes boil down to misperceiving fractions. We see slews of statistics that are essentially fractions, such as percentages, probabilities, frequencies, and rates, and we tend to misinterpret them. Sometimes bad actors manipulate us by cherry-picking data or distorting how information is presented; other times, sloppy communicators inadvertently mislead us. In many cases, we fool ourselves and have only our own minds to blame. Zimring also explores the counterintuitive reason that these flaws might benefit us, demonstrating that individual error can be highly advantageous to problem solving by groups. Blending key scientific research in cognitive psychology with accessible real-life examples, Partial Truths helps readers spot the fallacies lurking in everyday information, from politics to the criminal justice system, from religion to science, from business strategies to New Age culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCognitive psychology. 0aCritical thinking. 0aSuicide victims. 7aMATHEMATICS / Probability & Statistics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/zimr2013840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231554077/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Packag